Good week for Lynnville-Sully Hawk Volleyball.
On Monday, August 31, the Lynnville-Sully varsity volleyball team won their first SICL Conference match of the season, winning 3-0 by scores of 25-19, 25-18, and 25-23. On Tuesday, September 1, the Hawks defeated Baxter, winning 3-1 by scores of 25-18, 25-27, 25-21, 25-14.

post_text:
9th Grade Orientation Video

Incoming 9th graders and families,

In any normal school year, we would have typically held a freshmen orientation sometime in the spring of your 8th grade year. At that orientation, we try to answer questions about various topics such as graduation requirements, student schedules, eligibility, etc.

With the COVID-19 Pandemic, we obviously were not able to hold that event in person. Instead, Mrs. O'Halloran and I have put together a video for you to watch on your own time.

Please take a look, and get in touch if you have any questions.

Click here to watch the video: https://youtu.be/ZzbOhCLyK4E

Thanks!

Aaron Shipley
HS Principal

post_text:
Prom 2020 Changes

After careful consideration and input from the Jasper County Health Department and a group of Lynnville-Sully
After-Prom Parents, the school district has determined that we will not sponsor Prom 2020 activities .

After much discussion and research, it became clear that sponsoring traditional prom activities at the school was
not manageable with current health recommendations and guidelines.

The school district has been in contact with a parent group that plans to organize a modified, non school sanctioned event . It is the district’s understanding that this group of parents plans to send out more details about their event to parents and students in the near future.

not manageable with current health recommendations and guidelines.

The school district has been in contact with a parent group that plans to organize a modified, non school sanctioned event . It is the district’s understanding that this group of parents plans to send out more details about their event to parents and students in the near future.

post_text:
Week of May 25 - LYNNVILLE-SULLY HAWKS - FLASHBACK IN TIME

Event of the Week: 2018 Boys Track 800 Sprint Medley State Champions

This week, we will highlight the Hawks boys track 800 sprint medley relay team that set a state record with an epic chase to win our first state title in a relay since 2014. Sage Zylstra, Nate Stock, Corey McCoy, and Tyson Vander Linden added gold medals to their HS track careers. Vander Linden anchors with a 48.5, 400m split, and the 1:33:83 time set is the fastest ever in Class 1A.

Click the following link to watch the state championship relay race:
https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLTlv5DQWmAmJjFKy_mZS8cdeG-cKPGWw7

Even though Lynnville-Sully does not have sports due to COVID-19, we are highlighting some of the best games in Lynnville-Sully history. One game/event from multiple sports will be shown each week in a segment we call: Flashback in Time. NOTE: The games highlighted on Flashback in Time are not ranked by order of importance.

post_text: Today's Kindness Week dress-up challenge is to wear your craziest outfit! Have fun and be creative with what you wear to show others that kindness matters. The focus for today is to be kind to yourself. There are lots of way to take care of yourself - eat healthy foods, drink lots of water, get some exercise, take a nap, or just relax doing one of your favorite activities. Whatever you choose, make sure you remember that when we take care of ourselves, we get refueled and can then be more helpful to others. Don't forget to snap a picture of your crazy outfit choice or an example of how you are taking care of yourself and put it in the comments section of this post to show how you are taking part in Kindness Week!

post_text: LS Hawks: Yesterday was full of sunshine and today is supposed to be more of the same. This would be a great day to grab a large blanket, a couple of great books, and some of your favorite people to celebrate the wonderful weather by reading outside. Feeling the warmth of the sun on your face is such a positive experience and we understand that lots of kids would rather be outside than cooped up indoors. We also understand the importance of having students read every day, including our kids who are transitioning from “learning to read” to “reading to learn.” Why not combine both important needs by finding the perfect spot in your yard to enjoy an amazing book? That sounds like a win-win situation! Ask an adult to capture the moment and include the picture in the comment section of this post. We would love to see your perfect reading spot surrounded by sunshine as we say farewell to the month of March!

post_text:
L-S Hawks: The official first day of spring for 2020 was one week ago and there are signs of the new season all around us! The next time you are outside getting some fresh air and enjoying the sunshine, we encourage you to go on a spring scavenger hunt. See how many of the following items you can spot in your yard or when you go on a nature walk with your family.
*Buds on trees or bushes
*Geese flying in the sky
*Squirrels having a snack
*Animal tracks in the mud
*Flowers sprouting
*Robins, sparrows, or red wing black birds
*Frogs in ponds or shallow streams
After your scavenger hunt, ask an adult to share a picture of your adventure or post a list of the items you were able to spot. Happy hunting and good luck!

post_text: L-S Hawks: Reading is a big part of what we do at school every day and we hope you are finding ways to continue reading at home. In our classrooms, you have lots of opportunities to read with your friends and classmates through workstations and other activities. Since we are all at home right now, your typical reading partners are not available to you. That means we get to be creative in finding new partners to share in our reading time. Today’s challenge is to find a furry friend (pet dog, cat, etc.) or a stuffed friend (favorite stuffed animal) to become your new reading buddy. Ask an adult at home to post a picture of you entertaining your new reading partners with a great book and post it in the comments section below. Enjoy your time with books today!

post_text: L-S Hawks - Fractions are everywhere! A fraction is a way to talk about whole objects and equal parts of objects. A fun and easy way to include fractions into your conversations at home is through food. Help an adult at home cook a meal and look for fractions in the recipes. Make a sandwich for lunch or a snack and see if you can divide it up into equal pieces to share with others at home. How many pieces would you have to cut the sandwich into? What fraction of the sandwich would you get to eat? Take a picture of your fun combining fractions and food and post it in the comments section to share what you discovered. Happy cooking!

Lynnville-Sully Community School District School Closure due to COVID-19 (Coronavirus)

As of Monday March 16, 2020, all Lynnville-Sully facilities will be closed for four weeks (as per Gov. Kim Reynolds’ recommendation ). School is scheduled to resume on Monday, April 13, 2020. All school activities/practices between March 16 and April 13 have been canceled or postponed. As always, our first priority is the health and safety of our students, families and staff. Information from the Department of Education and Iowa Department of Public Health continues to evolve rapidly. As information becomes available, the school district will continue to provide updates on our website, social media, and via email to families and staff.

For detailed information, please go to the school's website: www.lshawks.org

Please direct questions to Shane Ehresman, Superintendent Phone: 641-594-4445 extension 103
Email: ehresman@lshawks.com

post_text: Lynnville-Sully Community Education Foundation (LSCEF) Book Giveaway. Friday, March 13 was an exciting morning for K-5 students! post_text: Congratulations to Lynnville-Sully cross country team members on a fantastic SICL conference meet last night. The girls' team placed 2nd, only 10 points from first. The boys' team placed third, only two points out of 2nd and 15 points from first. Greenlee Smock was the individual conference champion in the girls' race. Caitlin Alberts earned all-conference honors finishing 5th, and Megan Van Zante honorable mention all-conference at 11th. James Gruver was runner-up in the boys’ race earning all-conference recognition, while Gentry Walston was honorable mention all-conference at 11th. Coaches: Darin Arkema & Chris Hansen. Great job Hawks!!

post_text: Lynnville-Sully 7th graders took an educational hike today and learned about nature at the Jacob Krumm Nature Preserve from Katie Cantu, Naturalist. Jacob Krumm Nature Preserve is a 450-acre park and nature preserve located ¼ mile north of the Lynnville exit, off I-80. The preserve is located in Jasper County. On the rolling terrain of the preserve are to be found prairies, savanna, woodlands, a 25 acre lake, a marsh, ponds, and wildlife plantings.

post_text: Kindergarten Round Up for the class of 2032 will be held in two sessions on Wednesday, Apr. 10. Each attendee has previously been assigned either the morning (9-11 a.m.) or afternoon (1-3 p.m.) session. During that time, children will meet the teachers, familiarize themselves with the classroom, and undergo testing. If you have any questions, please call the elementary office at 641-594-4445. Parents should drop off and pick up their children at the south doors of the elementary school. The Hometown Press will take pictures of each group at 9:10 a.m. and 1:10 p.m. There is no school for current kindergartners on Wednesday, Apr. 10.
